    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_403995402" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/403995402" />
    <a title="Andree" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2863963-andree"><img alt="Andree" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/403995402?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andree" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andree" href="/user/show/2863963-andree">Andree</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2863963-andree?shelf=2014">2014</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer403995402" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1512276381325911693">Entertaining enough, but also completely ridiculous and sensationalized. Seriously, this is one of Anne of Green Gables&apos; ridiculous early stories. Or Emily of New Moon&apos;s novel that she consulted Father Cassidy on, which had him shaking his head muttering, &quot;Another one of the seven original plots in the world.&quot;<br/><br/>No joke: <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[Young girl chafes under a reclusive and tyrranical grandfather and longs for freedom. Enter mysterious stranger who falls in love with her and sweeps her away after </span></span>
  <span id="freeText1512276381325911693" style="display:none">Entertaining enough, but also completely ridiculous and sensationalized. Seriously, this is one of Anne of Green Gables' ridiculous early stories. Or Emily of New Moon's novel that she consulted Father Cassidy on, which had him shaking his head muttering, "Another one of the seven original plots in the world."<br /><br />No joke: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Young girl chafes under a reclusive and tyrranical grandfather and longs for freedom. Enter mysterious stranger who falls in love with her and sweeps her away after a hasty marriage. She 's happy for a year or so and then surprise! Turns out he has a prior wife and son. She runs away. There is much running and hiding, once by way of a laundry hamper, once by disguising self as a boy. There is a stint hiding in a convent, a faked death, a second near (real) marriage, falling in love with a noble priest (who loves her back, but remains sacred to his vows), a stint shut up in a mad-house by obsessive-lover dude (who is also a murderer), going to live with dude's first wife and son and becoming a happy family. And then, the end (just when all is safe), a summons from grandpa because of an inheritance, which causes vengeful obsessed villain to crash into the priest's (his rival's) boat to get rid of the competition and spirit her away. Except surprise! It was her boat he crashed into not the priest and she's dead. But s'okay, because now she and priest dude can be happy together " in the next life" where obsessed dude can't hurt them. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I really think that synopsis speaks for itself.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1512276381325911693" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


