    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_75938694" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/75938694" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2596926-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1249438363p2/2596926.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/75938694?book_show_action=true">Oct 27, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/2596926-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer75938694" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1431572989922733488">I&apos;m reading all of Louisa May Alcott&apos;s early thrillers - but not all together, whew! They are overblown, heaving page-turners, usually with impossibly noble/beautiful/charming/accomplished heroines who either make a mistake in their choice of love interest or are pursued unwillingly. As I begin each of these I think well I want to read them all so I&apos;ll just keep going, and then almost inevitably I get caught up by Alcott&apos;s plotting or writing style and end up enjoying the book. They are not grea</span>
  <span id="freeText1431572989922733488" style="display:none">I'm reading all of Louisa May Alcott's early thrillers - but not all together, whew! They are overblown, heaving page-turners, usually with impossibly noble/beautiful/charming/accomplished heroines who either make a mistake in their choice of love interest or are pursued unwillingly. As I begin each of these I think well I want to read them all so I'll just keep going, and then almost inevitably I get caught up by Alcott's plotting or writing style and end up enjoying the book. They are not great literature but they are better than the few contemporary romance novels I've read. In this book, the heroine is seventeen when we first meet her and is of course witty, courageous, and pert, but innocent withal. And here's the problem with these novels. Alcott wants to have it all ways - the heroine is immaculately innocent, quick to blush, and articulate in denouncing lack of principle. But she also romps through adventures and meets up with the most despicable villains and is never tarnished. She is married to a dreadful man for a year but at the end of the year the reader cannot imagine they have ever gone to bed together. But of course this isn't Alcott's fault; it's the time she was writing in and the expectations of her publisher and readers. This book was actually never published in her lifetime and one wonders why. I enjoyed it and will continue to read these old thrillers before I move on to Alcott's acknowledged novels.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1431572989922733488" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


